field left blank. An option for \u0022Allow Nulls\u0022 is checked, indicating that this foreign key can accept null values. Below this, the \u0022FK Field Name\u0022 is specified as \u0022refPriorityId\u0022 and the \u0022Caption\u0022 is labeled as \u0022Priority.\u0022 At the bottom, two buttons are visible: \u0022Next\u0022 and \u0022Cancel,\u0022 indicating the user can proceed or exit the wizard.\n\n\n  \n In case the target field already has a Lookup created, you can select it here. Also, if the field should be obligatory, then deselect the option  Allow Nulls . \n This is what the wizard will create for you: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/089005b6f5cde5868be6bae34750080785478901.png]\nDescription: This image displays a dialog for a \u0022Create Foreign Key Wizard,\u0022 designed for creating a foreign key with specific parameters. The visible text includes: \u0022This wizard creates a Foreign key with this parameters:\u0022, followed by the parameters listed as: \u0022Master Entity: Task,\u0022 \u0022Foreign Entity: Priority,\u0022 \u0022Foreign Field: Id,\u0022 \u0022Foreign Key: refPriorityId,\u0022 \u0022Lookup:,\u0022 \u0022Caption: Priority,\u0022 and \u0022Allow null: False.\u0022 There are buttons labeled \u0022Start\u0022 and \u0022Cancel\u0022 at the bottom of the dialog. The purpose seems to facilitate the configuration of foreign key relationships in a database schema.\n\n\n  \n And here is your FK field created after you click on the  Start  button: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/d82edcdb4356d0215c21bfdfb979ae74b1183121.png]\nDescription: Create Foreign Key Wizard is displayed with a title at the top. The interface includes a left panel showing \u0022Found In\u0022 with one entry: \u0022Task\\refPriorityId\u0022, represented with an icon indicating a database field. The column labeled \u0022Type\u0022 lists \u0022Database Field\u0022. At the bottom right, there are two buttons labeled \u0022Show Result\u0022 and \u0022Close\u0022. The purpose of the interface is to assist users in creating foreign key relationships in a database schema.\n\n\n  \n When you click on the  Show result  button, the wizard will get you into the  Find results  tab in the Model browser: \n   \n When you double-click on the new field created, you will jump to the Model browser tab and see your new FK field also there: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b92b43e7874c0cc0c3528e42fd3f3fe7d02a56a.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a hierarchical structure for a data model or service related to task management, labeled \u0022taskman.\u0022 It includes several categories: \u0022Priority,\u0022 \u0022Status,\u0022 and \u0022Task.\u0022 Under the \u0022Task\u0022 category, there is a subcategory labeled \u0022_Ancestors,\u0022 which contains a section titled \u0022Fields.\u0022 The listed fields include \u0022Description,\u0022 \u0022DueDate,\u0022 and \u0022Name.\u0022 Additionally, there is a field called \u0022refPriorityId.\u0022 This structure suggests the organization of attributes and references within a task management system, indicating where various data points may be categorized and accessed.\n\n\n  \n Now double-click the field to see the details of it, and all the fields that the wizard filled in for you: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4aa930c6a23efc2e70f34b4b7db209a75eb86033.png]\nDescription: The image displays a database field configuration for \u0060refPriorityId\u0060 in a data schema context. In the \u0022Info\u0022 section, the field name is noted as \u0060refPriorityId\u0060. Under the \u0022Entity Column\u0022 category, the caption is labeled as \u0060Priority\u0060, with a data type specified as \u0060UniqueIdentifier\u0060 and a data length of \u00600\u0060. The settings also allow null values. The \u0022Foreign Key\u0022 section indicates the foreign key entity as \u0060Priority\u0060 and the foreign key field as \u0060Id\u0060. In the \u0022Mapping\u0022 section, the mapped column name is listed as \u0060refPriorityId\u0060, and the mapped data type is provided as well as \u0060FieldMapping\u0060. The purpose appears to be defining the schema and relationships for database interactions related to priorities.\n\n\n  \n   Manual procedure \n In order to be able to create a Foreign key field manually, you have to create the database field for it first. The DataType of a field that holds a foreign key needs to be set as  UniqueIdentifier : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:44:23"},"vector":[-0.03671683,-0.0026667817,-0.052120265,0.010919793,0.015160816,0.0051744026,0.023046846,-0.013809211,0.0032034465,0.015071081,-0.023359679,-0.0014190186,-0.0231391,0.025275242,0.021654207,0.013703592,0.009527583,-0.029155148,0.040745594,0.0010625165,-0.040720154,0.01990816,0.05204124,-0.0123253,0.0060716313,0.032655522,-0.0020760526,-0.025308324,-0.003663357,-0.027555121,0.018807247,-0.05230279,-0.027919259,-0.051213074,-0.009637365,-0.018868417,0.0130195115,0.0042700553,-0.04764729,0.023180684,-0.019892002,-0.0135040255,0.006584323,0.012356224,0.00825686,-0.020858401,-0.0073583922,-0.013274776,-0.0047471947,-0.041488133,-0.07316167,-0.01581873,0.021310966,-0.028133392,0.07599053,0.035360154,-0.056006443,-0.0014976766,-0.051870085,-0.0046847328,0.024365371,-0.031941824,0.012397609,-0.0054924735,0.0088624945,-0.011319497,-0.044208445,-0.014850604,-0.013540227,-0.06490141,0.019552536,0.045358777,-0.054810423,-0.025073215,-0.03146024,0.006593041,-0.009075255,0.0382018,-0.025411857,0.02340715,-0.021378506,0.010364692,0.0142698735,0.036971085,0.041560795,0.0282358,-0.008905113,0.06932818,0.014617373,0.014417229,-0.061767273,0.0060673472,0.07231103,-0.061995544,0.011075457,-0.02102747,-0.024215888,0.